@lunablackxxx Because as we know, w/ ethic families it’s typically the case that the woman of the house does ALL the cooking/cleaning/entertaining - while the men are catered to left, right & centre. Gender specific roles at home are just the way life rolls, especially w/ old-school ethnics.

@lunablackxxx This behaviour is quite commonplace in the ethic community. My late mother (a Hungarian) always dropped into her parents home unannounced. My poor nagymama was always accommodating and loved her grandchildren, but still - it placed pressure on her to prepare food/beverages.

@lunablackxxx No-one should ever turn up unannounced, ever. Not friends, family, clients, anyone. I’ve always considered it the height of rudeness. I wouldn’t do the ‘in the neighbourhood; can I pop in?’ either. Plans should always be made in advance. Surprise visits are a big no-no for me.

@lunablackxxx I used to live with my former fiancé, a Greek, whose entire family would turn up unannounced on a Sunday. I would have just finished doing my housework and cleaning up after breakast and the entire family would arrive. I never sat down in that home to relax.

@lunablackxxx You’ve got to be kidding me. Someone actually did this to you? What kind of person actually does this! I’m so sorry you encountered this. I find it unsettling, someone I know in my personal life just popping in. I would be rattled if a client did this. This is just disturbing.
